04827nam a22007695i 9780812293661DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162004pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1002232141  a(OCoLC)1004868121  a(OCoLC)1011467991  a(OCoLC)1013938687  a(OCoLC)999360524  a97808122936617 a10.9783/97808122936612doi  a(DE-B1597)473299  a(OCoLC)959918616  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aDK771.D3 B 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a957.70862231 aBloch, Alexia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Museum at the End of the World :bEncounters in the Russian Far East /cAlexia Bloch, Laurel Kendall. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2016] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b41 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface: The Museum at the End of Whose World? -- tNote on Transliteration -- tMap of the Russian Far East -- t1. Across the Bering Strait and Through the Looking Glass -- t2. Chukotka: At the Edge of a Crumbling Empire -- t3. Magadan: The End of History -- t4. Anadyr: Tundra Town in Pastel -- t5. Khabarovsk: Embroidering the Border -- t6. Petropavlovsk: Once Almost a Boom Town -- t7. Esso and the Way There -- t8. In the Entourage of the Fisher King -- t9. Again Petropavlovsk -- tEpilogues -- tNotes -- tSelected Sources -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA little over a century ago the American Museum of Natural History launched its ambitious Jesup North Pacific Expedition to learn more about the peoples inhabiting the remote easternmost extension of Siberia and the northwest coast of North America. In The Museum at the End of the World: Encounters in the Russian Far East, anthropologists Alexia Bloch and Laurel Kendall tell the story of their journey through this same part of the world in 1998, retracing the old expedition as they link the expedition legacy of artifacts, photographs, and archival material from the museum in New York to the present-day descendants of its subjects.Contrasting the time of the Jesup expedition with their own travel, the authors reveal a physical and cultural landscape that was profoundly shaken over the past century, first by Soviet control and then by that empire's unraveling. The Museum at the End of the World is not the story of a heroic adventure but rather a series of conversations about Siberian culture with museum workers, native scholars, performers and artisans, and a great variety of ordinary people. They reveal a strong concern about past legacies, cultural preservation, and their uncertain future as they struggle to reinvent themselves.The authors' combination of travelers' curiosity and professional inquiry provide a compelling portrait of life in the Russian Far East and a meditation on the fate of culture and tradition in the face of hard economic times and sudden autonomy after decades of state control.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aAnthropology.  aFolklore.  aLinguistics.1 aKendall, Laurel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229366140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812293661423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812293661.jpg  a978-3-11-045954-8  University of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter